fields.Title: Medicinal Purposes of the Pale: "It seems to contain descriptions of..."
fields.Dialogue Text: It seems to contain descriptions of the medicinal properties of various ingredients that may be gathered from the pale, as well as instructions for producing a variety of herbal remedies.

fields.Dialogue Text: I don't even know what this 'pale' thing is, how could I have walked through it?

fields.Dialogue Text: And on your walks, do you stop to meditate on the nature of your being?

fields.Dialogue Text: The rue and aloe vera make this poultice ideal for alleviating minor injuries and inflammation. It won't do anything for your hangover, though.

fields.Title: Medicinal Purposes of the Pale: "Would you like to try again?"
fields.Dialogue Text: Would you like to try again?

fields.Title: You: "Great, so where can I get all this..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Great, so where can I get all this stuff?

fields.Dialogue Text: This book contains serious ancient wisdom, not whacko conspiracy theories. If you don't respect it, it will never reveal its secrets.

fields.Dialogue Text: You close the book and find yourself staring at the familiar cover once more.

fields.Dialogue Text: What? No.

fields.Dialogue Text: Have you taken any walks through the pale recently?

fields.Dialogue Text: The book is frustratingly vague on this topic, but it seems that if you've walked through the pale, you would know it.

fields.Title: You: "No, I don't."
fields.Dialogue Text: No, I don't.

fields.Title: You: "I could, I just don't feel like it."
fields.Dialogue Text: I could, I just don't feel like it.

fields.Title: Medicinal Purposes of the Pale: "That feeling is the weight of socie..."
fields.Dialogue Text: That feeling is the weight of society bearing down on you. Until you get out from under it, you will never feel true freedom.

fields.Title: You: "Mix it with a dram of whiskey."
fields.Dialogue Text: Mix it with a dram of whiskey.

fields.Dialogue Text: The ginger root will help with the nausea and the birch bark tea will help you flush out the toxins. The ginseng should give you more energy, as a nice bonus.

fields.Title: Medicinal Purposes of the Pale: "Would you like to try again?"
fields.Dialogue Text: Would you like to try again?

fields.Title: You: "Yeah, let's try again."
fields.Dialogue Text: Yeah, let's try again.

fields.Title: You: "I want to try concoct one of those..."
fields.Dialogue Text: I want to try concoct one of those hangover-cures again.

fields.Dialogue Text: What's a pharmacopoeia?

fields.Dialogue Text: Your partner is even more repressed than you are. It would do you both a world of good to spend a little more time getting in touch with your bodies.

fields.Dialogue Text: (Rub your hands together.) Alright, book, let's see what you got.

fields.Dialogue Text: No, this stuff is all a bunch of hooey, anyway. (Close the book.)

fields.Dialogue Text: Alright, time to get back to work. (Close the book.)

fields.Dialogue Text: Well, yeah, on your junk, too.

fields.Dialogue Text: You come across the following explanation: "While modern pharmacopoeia are continually updated by so-called 'experts' based on the results of 'clinical trials,' readers will find assembled here the timeless wisdom relied upon by generations of traditional Seolite medicine practitioners, Mesque mystics, and Iilmaraan folk doctors."

fields.Title: Medicinal Purposes of the Pale: "You're doing everything as you shou..."
fields.Dialogue Text: You're doing everything as you should. Regular pale meditation has been shown to help keep your body lithe and strong, your mind alert and expansive...

fields.Title: Medicinal Purposes of the Pale: "There's nothing in here that speaks..."
fields.Dialogue Text: There's nothing in here that speaks to hangovers directly. However, while browsing through the various descriptions you become convinced that you could assemble something from the ingredients listed here. Want to give it a shot?

fields.Title: Medicinal Purposes of the Pale: "A note of caution, however. Be sure..."
fields.Dialogue Text: A note of caution, however. Be sure to limit your exposure to the pale to no more than an hour a day, and no more than three hours total per week.

fields.Title: Authority: "Nor should you. Nudity is *shameful..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Nor should you. Nudity is *shameful*. No officer of the law should ever be caught *sans pantalones*.

fields.Title: You: "I could, but Kim's here."
fields.Dialogue Text: I could, but Kim's here.

fields.Dialogue Text: I don't have time for this.

fields.Dialogue Text: The ginger root will help with the nausea and the birch bark tea will help you flush out the toxins. The pomegranate seeds are a natural aphrodisiac, as a nice bonus.

fields.Dialogue Text: The ginger and aloe vera make this poultice ideal for the treatment of arthritis. It won't do anything for your hangover, though.

fields.Dialogue Text: If only you could find one of these right now and drink the shit out of it. The book said it's good for you, so it would be okay.

fields.Title: You: "Yeah, let's try again."
fields.Dialogue Text: Yeah, let's try again.

fields.Title: Medicinal Purposes of the Pale: "Very well. First, choose a base ing..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Very well. First, choose a base ingredient.

fields.Dialogue Text: From the pale, of course. Or perhaps from some enterprising entroponaut. Where you would find one of those, though, the book does not say.

fields.Dialogue Text: Anything about curing an apocalyptic hangover?

fields.Dialogue Text: They're a series of psychic nodes located throughout your body. Unfortunately, the stresses of modern life often cause us to close off our agiogenous zones, which can result in all manner of physical and psychic ailments...

fields.Dialogue Text: There are a number of Seolite tonics that promise to improve your short-term memory, but nothing that speaks to your condition.

fields.Dialogue Text: This tastes so bad it can only be good for you. According to the pharmacopoeia, it should help you perform your *marital obligations*.

fields.Dialogue Text: Be that as it may, it might have been useful to have such a thing for the trials you'll soon be facing. It's a shame you can't get your hands on these ingredients.

fields.Title: Medicinal Purposes of the Pale: "You imagine yourself with a mug of..."
fields.Dialogue Text: You imagine yourself with a mug of this tea in a chair by the window. It's a beautiful image, but will it ever come true for you?

fields.Title: Medicinal Purposes of the Pale: "Remote Viewers Division? What kind..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Remote Viewers Division? What kind of woo-woo shit is that?

fields.Title: You: "A sprig of fresh mint."
fields.Dialogue Text: A sprig of fresh mint.

fields.Title: You: "A few pomegranate seeds."
fields.Dialogue Text: A few pomegranate seeds.

fields.Title: Electrochemistry: "You should drink it anyway."
fields.Dialogue Text: You should drink it anyway.

fields.Title: You: "Mmmm. (Savour the feeling a moment..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Mmmm. (Savour the feeling a moment longer.)

fields.Title: You: "Maybe?"

fields.Dialogue Text: A spoonful of sugar.

fields.Title: You: "Some wild ginseng root."
fields.Dialogue Text: Some wild ginseng root.

fields.Dialogue Text: The very thought of this tea causes your muscles to relax and your mind to clear. You're more present and in control than you were a moment ago.

fields.Dialogue Text: You close the book and find yourself staring at the familiar cover once more.

fields.Dialogue Text: Oh... then I do, very much so. I meditate *all the time*.

fields.Dialogue Text: The combination of mint and birch bark make this tea relaxing and good for the digestion. It won't do much for your hangover, though.

fields.Dialogue Text: Whoever wrote this never heard of the hair of the dog. Fuck this book. See if there's a bar open that'll still serve you.

fields.Dialogue Text: It's all quackery, in other words.

fields.Dialogue Text: Finally, something to calm the angry spirits that have been plaguing you.

fields.Dialogue Text: Yes, twice a week.

fields.Dialogue Text: The tincture you've invented sounds intriguing, but its medicinal value is suspect, to say the least. Safe to say it won't cure your hangover.

fields.Dialogue Text: You glance over at the lieutenant, who is standing, as usual, with his hands neatly folded behind his back. What he's thinking about, if he's thinking about anything at all, is absolutely opaque to you.

fields.Dialogue Text: You probably can't even take off your pants, can you?

fields.Dialogue Text: Flipping through the book you find a number of sections on the general benefits of the pale. A large pharmacopoeia makes up nearly half of the book.
